You can get array keys using `Object.keys()` and then loop through your array and then keys.

Then to create the full thing you&#39;re after:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var a = [
      {&quot;Destination&quot;: &quot;Usa&quot;},
      {&quot;Type&quot;: &quot;commercial&quot;},
      {&quot;Transport&quot;: &quot;plane&quot;},
      {&quot;price&quot;: &quot;501-700&quot;}
    ];

    var url = &quot;https://localhost/appname&quot;;
    for (var i = 0; i &lt; a.length; i++) {
      var keys = Object.keys(a[i]);
      for (var k = 0; k &lt; keys.length; k++) {
        if (i == 0) {
          url += &quot;?&quot;;
        } else {
          url += &quot;&amp;&quot;;
        }
        url += keys[k] + &quot;=&quot; + a[i][keys[k]];
      }
    }
    console.log(url);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Basically, you can use `map` to traverse through each of the objects in the array.

For each object in the array, I am also assuming there to be multiple key value pairs.
`Object.entries(obj)` returns an array of [key,value] pair tuples (arrays).

By joining these with &#39;&amp;&#39; and joining the outer array of objs by &#39;&amp;&#39; you get the desired result. You could use toLowerCase for removing any case sensitive issues


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let data = [{Destination: &quot;Usa&quot;}, {Type: &quot;commercial&quot;}, {Transport: &quot;plane&quot;}, {price: &quot;501-700&quot;}]
    let result = &#39;http://localhost/appname?&#39; + data.map(obj =&gt; Object.entries(obj).map(([key,value]) =&gt; key.toLowerCase()+&quot;=&quot;+value).join(&#39;&amp;&#39;)).join(&#39;&amp;&#39;);

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

